="Go to the profile of Sam Decrock"></a></div><div class="u-flex1 u-paddingLeft15 u-overflowHidden"><div class="u-lineHeightTightest"><a class="ds-link ds-link--styleSubtle ui-captionStrong u-inlineBlock link link--darken link--darker"   href="https://medium.com/@decrocksam?source=post_header_lockup" data-action="show-user-card" data-action-source="post_header_lockup" data-action-value="8f8336fa1565" data-action-type="hover" data-user-id="8f8336fa1565" dir="auto">Sam Decrock</a><span class="followState js-followState" data-user-id="8f8336fa1565"><button class="button button--smallest u-noUserSelect button--withChrome u-baseColor--buttonNormal button--withHover button--unblock js-unblockButton u-marginLeft10 u-xs-hide"  data-action="sign-up-prompt" data-sign-in-action="toggle-block-user" data-requires-token="true" data-redirect="https://medium.com/@decrocksam/amazon-echo-buttons-teardown-9f066a84f156" data-action-source="post_header_lockup"><span class="button-label  button-defaultState">Blocked</span><span class="button-label button-hoverState">Unblock</span></button><button class="button button--primary button--smallest u-noUserSelect button--withChrome u-accentColor--buttonNormal button--follow js-followButton u-marginLeft10 u-xs-hide"  data-action="sign-up-prompt" data-sign-in-action="toggle-subscribe-user" data-requires-token="true" data-redirect="https://medium.com/_/subscribe/user/8f8336fa1565" data-action-source="post_header_lockup-8f8336fa1565-------------------------follow_byline"><span class="button-label  button-defaultState js-buttonLabel">Follow</span><span class="button-label button-activeState">Following</span></button></span></div><div class="ui-caption ui-xs-clamp2 postMetaInline">computer science (reverse) engineer</div><div class="ui-caption postMetaInline js-testPostMetaInlineSupplemental"><time datetime="2018-01-03T17:04:49.333Z">Jan 3</time><span class="middotDivider u-fontSize12"></span><span class="readingTime" title="6 min read"></span></div></div></div></div></div></header><div class="postArticle-content js-postField js-notesSource js-trackedPost"  data-post-id="9f066a84f156" data-source="post_page" data-tracking-context="postPage"><section name="e9ea" class="section section--body section--first section--last"><div class="section-divider"><hr class="section-divider"></div><div class="section-content"><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--insetColumn"><h1 name="1cc1" id="1cc1" class="graf graf--h3 graf--startsWithDoubleQuote graf--leading graf--title">“echo buttons” teardown: no Bluetooth Low Energy!</h1></div><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--fullWidth"><figure name="c909" id="c909" class="graf graf--figure graf--layoutFillWidth graf-after--h3"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 56.3%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*87oXsp9DRbAeuo_rOzNW3Q.jpeg" data-width="3973" data-height="2235" data-is-featured="true" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/2000/1*87oXsp9DRbAeuo_rOzNW3Q.jpeg"></div></figure></div><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--insetColumn"><p name="276b" id="276b" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">As you may or may or may not know, I’m a big fan of of wireless buzzer buttons. I <a href="https://playsmashit.tumblr.com/post/149940750218/catch-it-and-smash-it" data-href="https://playsmashit.tumblr.com/post/149940750218/catch-it-and-smash-it" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">once built some myself</a> and eventually tried releasing them through <a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/smash-it/smash-it-lets-play-together" data-href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/smash-it/smash-it-lets-play-together" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">Kickstarter</a>, but failed. Our buttons, were packed with extra sensors to measure the acceleration and direction. It was more like a little joystick than a simple button. Creating them was too expensive for a starting company like us. Also, the Kickstarter campaign should have been more about the games you play with it rather than focussing on the hardware. We learned some valuable lessons from that experience, but the project currently sits on my shelf. I’m only taking them out to play our custom trivia game with friends. Occasionally some friends want to lend them out for a personalised quiz/trivia game.</p><p name="375e" id="375e" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p">Anyway, I was stumped as Amazon <a href="https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/27/16374906/amazon-echo-buttons-family-games-connected-alexa" data-href="https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/27/16374906/amazon-echo-buttons-family-games-connected-alexa" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">announced</a> they were going to sell wireless buzzer buttons! If I could repurpose them, I could use the Amazon Buttons with my software. That would lower my costs significantly and I could get project running again (building software only). I had to get my hands on some.</p><p name="d90f" id="d90f" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p">After ordering them via Amazon.co.uk and shipping them through <a href="https://www.borderlinx.com/" data-href="https://www.borderlinx.com/" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">Borderlinx</a> to Belgium, I finally had the change to ‘play’ with them. By ‘play’, I mean screwing them open and see what’s inside :-)</p><figure name="920e" id="920e" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 700px; max-height: 467px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 66.7%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*L4XIvBm9puh6_6cgog5QYA.jpeg" data-width="4272" data-height="2848" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*L4XIvBm9puh6_6cgog5QYA.jpeg" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*L4XIvBm9puh6_6cgog5QYA.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">Nice little box with a leaflet, 2 buttons and 4 AAA batteries.</figcaption></figure><figure name="3727" id="3727" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--figure"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 700px; max-height: 467px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 66.7%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*AIk6uemr3QNOXxTC2bLZOQ.jpeg" data-width="4272" data-height="2848" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*AIk6uemr3QNOXxTC2bLZOQ.jpeg" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*AIk6uemr3QNOXxTC2bLZOQ.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">The box and the buttons.</figcaption></figure><figure name="9fb8" id="9fb8" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--figure"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 700px; max-height: 467px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 66.7%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*cfzZi1ok5WmfemZjUTzaaw.jpeg" data-width="4272" data-height="2848" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*cfzZi1ok5WmfemZjUTzaaw.jpeg" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*cfzZi1ok5WmfemZjUTzaaw.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">The PCB.</figcaption></figure><figure name="951e" id="951e" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--figure"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 700px; max-height: 467px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 66.7%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*y5Vc3HipUx9HZ6N4oHZ-nQ.jpeg" data-width="4272" data-height="2848" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*y5Vc3HipUx9HZ6N4oHZ-nQ.jpeg" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*y5Vc3HipUx9HZ6N4oHZ-nQ.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">One of the 3 touch points used to make the button “click”.</figcaption></figure><p name="12c5" id="12c5" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">As you can see, the buttons don’t have a real “click” mechanism. Just 3 soft touch points. So hitting the button doesn’t give much satisfaction as I hoped.</p><p name="6d2d" id="6d2d" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p">Now how can I connect them to my own trivia software instead of the Amazon Echo? I thought they were gonna show up on <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/lightblue-explorer/id557428110?mt=8" data-href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/lightblue-explorer/id557428110?mt=8" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">LightBlue</a>, a BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy) scanner for iOS, but they didn’t. What, are these not Bluetooth buttons? Looking up their <a href="https://fccid.io/UUU-4612" data-href="https://fccid.io/UUU-4612" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">FCC ID</a> revealed that they are indeed using Bluetooth but its not clear what version or protocol.</p><h3 name="ed48" id="ed48" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p">Sniffing the Echo Buttons</h3><p name="566e" id="566e" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3">To figure out what nifty, do-not-connect-to-our-buttons-scheme they used, I bought the <a href="https://www.adafruit.com/product/2269" data-href="https://www.adafruit.com/product/2269" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">BLE sniffer from Adafruit</a>. I first had to find my old Windows laptop as the software runs best on Windows. After scanning and sniffing some of my own BLE buttons, I decided to give the Echo Buttons a try.</p><figure name="ff5b" id="ff5b" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 700px; max-height: 394px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 56.3%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*87oXsp9DRbAeuo_rOzNW3Q.jpeg" data-width="3973" data-height="2235" data-is-featured="true" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*87oXsp9DRbAeuo_rOzNW3Q.jpeg" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*87oXsp9DRbAeuo_rOzNW3Q.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">BLE Sniffer on the right, trying to sniff the communication between the Echo Buttons and the Echo Dot</figcaption></figure><p name="96f8" id="96f8" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">Putting them in “pairing mode” shows … absolutely nothing. Okay, hitting “Pair Alexa Gadget” in the Alexa app also shows… nothing. Here’s an empty Wireshark 😛</p><figure name="6c7c" id="6c7c" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 700px; max-height: 394px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 56.3%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*nIxmbODbM8ZqayOyfuFQlg.jpeg" data-width="4272" data-height="2403" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*nIxmbODbM8ZqayOyfuFQlg.jpeg" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*nIxmbODbM8ZqayOyfuFQlg.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">Nothing to see here.</figcaption></figure><p name="4dd9" id="4dd9" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">That sucks. What’s going on? Also, why the hell does the user need to put the buttons into “pairing mode”? And why can one only connect <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Echo-Buttons-Alexa-Gadget-Pack/dp/B072C4KCQH/" data-href="https://www.amazon.com/Echo-Buttons-Alexa-Gadget-Pack/dp/B072C4KCQH/" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">up to 4 buttons at a time</a>. This doesn’t smell like Bluetooth Low Energy at all! Actually, Bluetooth Low Energy is so cool you don’t need the user’s interaction to connect and you can connect up to 255 devices (theoretically).</p><h3 name="75e1" id="75e1" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p">Plain old Bluetooth Classic</h3><p name="ba55" id="ba55" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3">Ok, this might look as a stupid idea. If it’s true, it may come as a shock. Lets use the regular Bluetooth scanner on my 2012 Macbook Pro (which doesn’t have BLE). I should have tried this before, but was expecting the buttons to be BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy). Here it goes:</p></div><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--outsetColumn"><figure name="3774" id="3774" class="graf graf--figure graf--layoutOutsetCenter graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 1000px; max-height: 563px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 56.3%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*grZD_iFdeXDBhSLm3PmTig.jpeg" data-width="4272" data-height="2403" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*grZD_iFdeXDBhSLm3PmTig.jpeg" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/2000/1*grZD_iFdeXDBhSLm3PmTig.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">Echo Button shows up as regular (Bluetooth Classic) device on my Mac.</figcaption></figure></div><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--insetColumn"><p name="62eb" id="62eb" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">Oh… my… I can only think of one thing:</p><figure name="86c4" id="86c4" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 245px; max-height: 233px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 95.1%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*s6ll85A9cc1ht1HjWx0k4A.gif" data-width="245" data-height="233" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*s6ll85A9cc1ht1HjWx0k4A.gif"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xLg7g6URjsQ" data-href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xLg7g6URjsQ" class="markup--anchor markup--figure-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">© Heart of Dixie</a></figcaption></figure><p name="4051" id="4051" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">Come on Amazon, is this innovation? You are using a 20th century old technology, well sort of. It was first used in the year 2000 and Nokia had its first Bluetooth enabled phone in 2002. Thats over 16 years ago :-(</p><figure name="4833" id="4833" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 153px; max-height: 382px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 249.7%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*pN6JpPGaCJi-DB-FjrtGog.jpeg" data-width="153" data-height="382" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*pN6JpPGaCJi-DB-FjrtGog.jpeg"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">Nokia 6310i: first Bluetooth enabled Nokia, released in 2002</figcaption></figure><h3 name="f942" id="f942" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--figure">So what’s wrong with not using Bluetooth Low Energy?</h3><p name="d859" id="d859" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3">Ok, I might be overreacting, but still… Bluetooth Low Energy would have been a much better choice:</p><ul class="postList"><li name="f56f" id="f56f" class="graf graf--li graf-after--p">First of, “low energy” actually means it does not consume much energy. That means longer battery life.</li><li name="5d63" id="5d63" class="graf graf--li graf-after--li">Second, BLE devies don’t need user interaction to pair. Your fitness tacker, for example, doesn’t need explicit pairing. Meaning you don’t need to go to you iOS settings and connect to a new Bluetooth device. The app can just find it on its own.</li><li name="1af8" id="1af8" class="graf graf--li graf-after--li">Bluetooth allows <a href="https://www.quora.com/Why-does-Bluetooth-only-allow-7-simultaneous-slaves" data-href="https://www.quora.com/Why-does-Bluetooth-only-allow-7-simultaneous-slaves" class="markup--anchor markup--li-anchor" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">only up to 7 ‘slaves’</a>. This means only 7 buttons can be connected. Whereas BLE should allows up to 255 devices. iOS seems to have a <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13469502/maximum-number-of-peripherals-on-corebluetooth/13654052#13654052" data-href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13469502/maximum-number-of-peripherals-on-corebluetooth/13654052#13654052" class="markup--anchor markup--li-anchor" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">limit of 20</a>. Personally tested connecting up to 12 devices.</li><li name="849e" id="849e" class="graf graf--li graf-after--li">To develop Bluetooth classic devices, most of the time you need extra certification, like the <a href="https://developer.apple.com/programs/mfi/" data-href="https://developer.apple.com/programs/mfi/" class="markup--anchor markup--li-anchor" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">Apple MFI program</a>.</li></ul><h3 name="0384" id="0384" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--li">Bluetooth Protocol</h3><p name="a0aa" id="a0aa" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3">Figuring out the protocol would be a great next step. Before I start investing in a Bluetooth sniffer, let’s connect and see what we can do using the tools at hand.</p><p name="07c3" id="07c3" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p">After pairing the Echo Button using the standard MacOS pair settings, the Echo Button shows up in the System information screen as follows:</p><figure name="aa4d" id="aa4d" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 700px; max-height: 404px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 57.699999999999996%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*ZUGyw7aj4fx6MyYUa9lDpA.png" data-width="773" data-height="446" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*ZUGyw7aj4fx6MyYUa9lDpA.png" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*ZUGyw7aj4fx6MyYUa9lDpA.png"></div></figure><p name="ebf1" id="ebf1" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">I have no idea what a gadget, RFC SERVER or SPP SERVER is, but googling SPP SERVER brought me to RFCOMM which brought me to something called a “Bluetooth serial port”.</p><h4 name="93ba" id="93ba" class="graf graf--h4 graf-after--p">Communicating with a button using Node.js</h4><p name="df73" id="df73" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h4">As Node.js is my go-to-framework for everything, I will connecting to the Buttons using the <a href="https://github.com/eelcocramer/node-bluetooth-serial-port" data-href="https://github.com/eelcocramer/node-bluetooth-serial-port" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">node-bluetooth-serial-port</a> module. Using a <a href="https://gist.github.com/SamDecrock/334b45ca6043c9cc9877f05dca38d6cc" data-href="https://gist.github.com/SamDecrock/334b45ca6043c9cc9877f05dca38d6cc" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">simple script</a>, I could indeed connect to the button!</p></div><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--outsetColumn"><figure name="adcf" id="adcf" class="graf graf--figure graf--layoutOutsetCenter graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 1000px; max-height: 342px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 34.2%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*lRdxAEiMKbjFrrEn0ldbKw.png" data-width="1193" data-height="408" data-action="zoom" data-action-value="1*lRdxAEiMKbjFrrEn0ldbKw.png" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/2000/1*lRdxAEiMKbjFrrEn0ldbKw.png"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption">Node.js output of my script;</figcaption></figure></div><div class="section-inner sectionLayout--insetColumn"><p name="2bac" id="2bac" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure">As you can see, the second last byte changes as I press or release the button. I have no idea what the other bytes are or how to change the light on the button.</p><h3 name="0adf" id="0adf" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p">Next Steps</h3><p name="6da2" id="6da2" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3">Next step will be connecting (up to 7 😛) Echo buttons to my Macbook Pro and see if I can repurpose them and use them in my trivia software. I might need to buy the <a href="http://ubertooth.sourceforge.net/hardware/one/" data-href="http://ubertooth.sourceforge.net/hardware/one/" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">Ubertooth</a> to figure out the protocol. I’ll update this post as I find more.</p><h3 name="941e" id="941e" class="graf graf--h3 graf-after--p">Conclusion</h3><p name="a169" id="a169" class="graf graf--p graf-after--h3">What can I say about this finding? I’m baffled by this choice Amazon made. Have they done just it because it would be harder for a hacker like me to repurpose them. Did <a href="https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/27/heres-why-amazon-made-those-weird-echo-buttons/" data-href="https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/27/heres-why-amazon-made-those-weird-echo-buttons/" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">they invent it more than 10 years ago</a> when BLE didn’t exist yet? 😛</p><p name="4fd7" id="4fd7" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p">What baffles me more, is that <a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Echo-Buttons-Alexa-Gadget-pack/dp/B072C4KCQH" data-href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Echo-Buttons-Alexa-Gadget-pack/dp/B072C4KCQH" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">the product page</a> clearly states it’s compatible with Bluetooth Low Energy (Bluetooth 4.2):</p><figure name="ca48" id="ca48" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked" style="max-width: 514px; max-height: 83px;"><div class="aspectRatioPlaceholder-fill" style="padding-bottom: 16.1%;"></div><img class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*QL2wSIsq57vvwXTMM9p4yw.png" data-width="514" data-height="83" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*QL2wSIsq57vvwXTMM9p4yw.png"></div></figure><p name="9233" id="9233" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure graf--trailing">It sure makes the experience a lot cumbersome, having to manually pair first. Taking up to 30 seconds per button means 2 minutes of technical work before a user can play. And according to <a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Echo-Buttons-Alexa-Gadget-pack/product-reviews/B072C4KCQH" data-href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Echo-Buttons-Alexa-Gadget-pack/product-reviews/B072C4KCQH" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">the reviews</a>, there are a lot of issue with pairing the buttons. I’m not sure if it will catch on… We’ll see.</p></div></div></section></div><footer class="u-paddingTop10"><div class="container u-maxWidth740"><div class="row"><div class="col u-size12of12"></div></div><div class="row"><div class="col u-size12of12 js-postTags"><div class="u-paddingBottom10"><ul class="tags tags--postTags tags--borderless"><li><a class="link u-baseColor--link"   href="https://medium.com/tag/amazon-echo?source=post" data-action-source="post">Amazon Echo</a></li><li><a class="link u-baseColor--link"   href="https://medium.com/tag/buzzer-buttons?source=post" data-action-source="post">Buzzer Buttons</a></li><li><a class="link u-baseColor--link"   href="https://medium.com/tag/bluetooth-low-energy?source=post" data-action-source="post">Bluetooth Low Energy</a></li><li><a class="link u-baseColor--link"   href="https://medium.com/tag/bluetooth-2?source=post" data-action-source="post">Bluetooth 2</a></li></ul></div></div></div><section class="uiScale uiScale-ui--small uiScale-caption--regular u-borderTopLightest u-marginTop10 u-paddingTop20"><div class="ui-h3 u-textColorDarker u-fontSize22">One clap, two clap, three clap, forty?</div><p class="ui-body u-marginBottom20 u-textColorDark u-fontSize16">By clapping more or less, you can signal to us which stories really stand out.</p></section><div class="postActions js-postActionsFooter"><div class="u-flexCenter"><div class="u-flex1"><div class="multirecommend js-actionMultirecommend u-flexCenter u-width60" data-post-id="9f066a84f156" data-is-icon-29px="true" data-is-circle="true" data-has-recommend-list="true" data-source="post_actions_footer-----9f066a84f1